uent public debates about female appearance and the realities of feminine self-presentation. She argues that women played an active and thoughtful role in their embrace of modern consumer culture, even when it was at the risk of serious social, economic, and cultural penalties. The first book to fully examine the “Modern Girl”’s place in Canadian culture, The Modern Girl will be essential reading for all those interested in the history of gender, sexuality, and the body in the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBeauty, PersonalxSocial aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxCanada. 0aBeauty, PersonalxSocial aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aFeminine beauty (Aesthetics)xHistoryx20th centuryxCanada. 0aFeminine beauty (Aesthetics)zCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen in popular culturexHistoryx20th centuryxCanada. 0aWomen in popular culturezCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxEconomic conditionsx20th centuryxCanada. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsx20th centuryxCanada. 0aWomenzCanadaxEconomic conditionsy20th century. 0aWomenzCanadaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144261652340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442616523423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442616523.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles